{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474060"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11765"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11765"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.04,0.08,0.51,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104599"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4378"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11765"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86941"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"5002"},{"type":"tags","id":"11494"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6121"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104599"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 4-month old baby is routinely reviewed by their General Practitioner and is incidentally found to have a cardiac murmur.  The baby is growing and developing well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is a well-appearing, acyanotic baby. There is no periorbital or sacral oedema, and no hepatosplenomegaly. There is no radio-femoral delay. S1 and S2 are present. A 2/6 crescendo-decrescendo ejection systolic murmur is noted, heard loudest at the left lower sternal border which is heard maximally when the baby is lying flat. The murmur does not radiate.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this murmur?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic stenosis","Coarctation of the aorta","Pulmonary stenosis","Physiological","VSD"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA crescendo-decrescendo ejection systolic murmur, heard loudest at the left lower sternal border is typical of a physiological murmur (\u003Cstrong\u003EStill\u0027s murmur) \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich is the most common murmur heard in the paediatric population. The sound is thought to be made by the resonance of blood being ejected into the aorta, or by the vibration of the chordae tendinae. This murmur is louder when the patient is lying flat due to an increased venous return. \u003Cstrong\u003EAortic stenosis \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be heard maximally at the right upper sternal border, and can radiate to the carotids. A murmur associated with \u003Cstrong\u003ECoarctation of the aorta \u003C/strong\u003Ewould likely be heard maximally at the left upper sternal border, and you may expect to find radio-femoral delay. \u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary stenosis \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be heard maximally at the left upper sternal border and be ejection systolic in nature, loudest on inspiration, and radiates throughout the lung fields. Although VSDs are also heard maximally at the left lower sternal border, a \u003Cstrong\u003EVSD \u003C/strong\u003Ewould typically be pansystolic in nature.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The most common paediatric murmur is physiological - known as Still\u0027s murmur"],"references":["Doshi A. Innocent Heart Murmur. Cureus. 2018;.","Mahawattege A, Shearer L, Chambers A. Navigating heart murmurs in children [Internet]. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2023 [cited 2025 Jun 2]. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2025/june/navigating-heart-murmurs-in-children"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86941"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11765"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86941"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T23:31:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T23:31:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4378"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104599"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"desc